        "content": "<p>Yeah I just read that, I need to prove something</p>",
        "id": 507369152,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruize Chen",
        "timestamp": 1742591847
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think currently it's annoying to work with the fundamental group because it's not defeq to the homotopy class of paths from a point to itself (<a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Homotopy/Path.html#Path.Homotopic.Quotient\">Path.Homotopic.Quotient</a>), but the units in this type (\"Aut\" in category theory rather than \"End\"). This is being changed in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/22771\">#22771</a>.</p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"816344\">Aaron Liu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/How.20to.20deal.20with.20fundamental.20group.20.28homotopy.20class.29/near/507286021\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>To lift an element of the fundamental group, you define a lift for paths and prove that lifting two homotopic paths gives the same result</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is done <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/22771/files#diff-b268e5082c483c1a45e83200d1408602c0c830428d0aa220b5a85b23b6624fd6R355-R362\">in #22771</a> and it's a direct consequence of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Homotopy/Lifting.html#IsCoveringMap.liftPath_apply_one_eq_of_homotopicRel\">IsCoveringMap.liftPath_apply_one_eq_of_homotopicRel</a>.</p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"816344\">Aaron Liu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/How.20to.20deal.20with.20fundamental.20group.20.28homotopy.20class.29/near/507288385\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It looks like <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=FundamentalGroup.toPath#doc\">docs#FundamentalGroup.toPath</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=FundamentalGroup.fromPath#doc\">docs#FundamentalGroup.fromPath</a> both take the type argument as a bundled topological space, which is weird</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is being changed <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/22771/files#diff-c1d9a6fa6045d84ce4d2403198699e1223fe0c6d2708371f632d10c7038ad3d6R60\">in #22771</a>.</p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"366779\">Jz Pan</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/How.20to.20deal.20with.20fundamental.20group.20.28homotopy.20class.29/near/507305487\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Do we have universal covering spaces in mathlib? Maybe you can prove that R is the universal covering space of S^1.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It's shown <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/7596/files#diff-c563ddf022f7e01c57f6c9dcc01c33e85520597fb5c474dcc1c8ca152df47c8bR18-R19\">in #7596</a> that R-&gt;S^1 (AddCircle) is a covering map, and we know R is contractible and therefore simply-connected, so ...<br>\nI also <a href=\"\">commented</a> what generality we should aim for for mathlib.</p>",
        "id": 507388894,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1742603148
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/22771/files#diff-b268e5082c483c1a45e83200d1408602c0c830428d0aa220b5a85b23b6624fd6R419-R427\">The lifting criterion</a> will be used to show the group of deck transformations act transitively on the fibers if the covering map is Galois (the induced map between fundamental groups has normal image). (For the universal cover this is always the case since the image is trivial; in algebra we correspondingly know that the separable closure of a field is always Galois.)</p>",
        "id": 507389577,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1742603574
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But in the case of R -&gt; S^1 you start from a group action (by translations) which are the deck transformations so you don't need to construct them. If you fix a basepoint in <code>p ‚Åª¬π' {x}</code>, using <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/22771/files#diff-b268e5082c483c1a45e83200d1408602c0c830428d0aa220b5a85b23b6624fd6R358-R359\"><code>monodromy</code></a> you get a point in <code>p ‚Åª¬π' {x}</code> for each element in the fundamental group at <code>x</code>. Any two elements in <code>p ‚Åª¬π' {x}</code> differ by an element in the group (Z in this case), so you get a map from the fundamental group to Z, and you only have to show it's an isomorphism.</p>",
        "id": 507393634,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1742606069
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>See <a class=\"message-link\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/How.20to.20wisely.20state.20Homotopy.20lifting.20lemma/near/564787599\">#Is there code for X? &gt; How to wisely state Homotopy lifting lemma @ üí¨</a> for an update. I've made <code>FundamentalGroup</code> an abbrev and mathlib compiles without trouble. I defined a predicate <code>IsQuotientCoveringMap</code> (to be merged in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/7596\">#7596</a>) capturing principal G-bundles for discrete G, but not <code>IsGaloisCovering</code> or <code>DeckTransformation</code> yet.</p>",
        "id": 564788189,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1766187042
    }
]